      <!-- SEO Content -->
      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>Your Complete Pregnancy Week-by-Week Guide</h2>
        <p>Pregnancy lasts approximately 40 weeks from the first day of your last menstrual period. Each week brings new developments for your baby and changes in your body. Understanding what's happening at each stage helps you prepare, know what to expect, and identify when something might need medical attention.</p>

        <h3>How Pregnancy Weeks Are Counted</h3>
        <p>Pregnancy weeks are counted from the first day of your last menstrual period (LMP), not from conception. This means that during weeks 1 and 2, you aren't actually pregnant yet — conception typically occurs around week 2 or 3. By the time you miss your period and get a positive test, you're usually already about 4 weeks along.</p>

        <h3>Baby Size Comparisons by Week</h3>
        <p>One of the most popular ways to visualize your baby's growth is through fruit and vegetable comparisons. Your baby starts as a tiny poppy seed at week 4, grows to a blueberry by week 7, reaches the size of a lemon by week 14, and continues growing until reaching the size of a small watermelon at full term. These comparisons give you a tangible sense of your baby's size at each stage.</p>

        <h3>Key Pregnancy Milestones</h3>
        <p>Several important milestones mark the journey from conception to birth:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Week 6:</strong> First heartbeat can be detected via ultrasound</li>
          <li><strong>Week 10:</strong> NIPT blood test available for genetic screening</li>
          <li><strong>Week 12:</strong> End of first trimester — miscarriage risk drops significantly</li>
          <li><strong>Week 16–20:</strong> First fetal movements may be felt</li>
          <li><strong>Week 20:</strong> Anatomy scan — baby's sex can often be determined</li>
          <li><strong>Week 24:</strong> Viability milestone — survival possible with intensive care</li>
          <li><strong>Week 37:</strong> Full term — baby's lungs are typically mature</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Common Symptoms Throughout Pregnancy</h2>
        <p>Pregnancy symptoms vary widely between individuals and even between different pregnancies for the same person. First trimester symptoms often include nausea, extreme fatigue, breast tenderness, and frequent urination. The second trimester typically brings relief from nausea but may introduce back pain, round ligament pain, and visible body changes. The third trimester often involves Braxton Hicks contractions, swelling in the feet and ankles, heartburn, and difficulty sleeping as the baby grows larger.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">How big is my baby each week of pregnancy?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Baby size grows from a tiny poppy seed at week 4 to the size of a watermelon at week 40. Common comparisons include a blueberry at week 7, a lemon at week 14, a banana at week 20, an eggplant at week 28, and a pumpkin at week 38. Your baby's actual length ranges from about 0.04 inches at week 4 to over 20 inches at birth.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What are the three trimesters of pregnancy?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">The first trimester spans weeks 1–12, when major organs form and pregnancy symptoms are often most intense. The second trimester covers weeks 13–27, often called the "honeymoon period" as energy returns and the baby grows rapidly. The third trimester runs from week 28 to birth (around week 40), when the baby gains weight, lungs mature, and your body prepares for delivery.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">When can I find out the gender of my baby?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Gender can potentially be determined as early as week 10 through non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) blood work. The anatomy scan ultrasound at around week 20 is the most common way to find out the baby's sex, though some providers may be able to identify it as early as weeks 16–18 by ultrasound.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What are common pregnancy symptoms by trimester?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">First trimester symptoms include nausea (morning sickness), fatigue, breast tenderness, and frequent urination. Second trimester symptoms include back pain, round ligament pain, visible baby bump, and increased appetite. Third trimester symptoms include Braxton Hicks contractions, swelling in feet and ankles, heartburn, and difficulty sleeping. Symptoms vary greatly between individuals.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">When is a baby considered viable outside the womb?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">The viability milestone is generally reached around week 24 of pregnancy. At this point, with intensive medical care in a neonatal ICU, a baby has a chance of survival outside the womb. Survival rates improve significantly with each additional week — by week 28 survival rates exceed 90% with proper medical care, and by week 34 outcomes are generally excellent.</div>
        </div>
